5%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hether reform of the existing system (for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, Community Budgets, Government grants, formulas and taxes such as stamp duty) would be a precursor to, or run along with, large-scale constitutional change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reform of the existing system is essential, but t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is no preference as to whether it would precede or be part of large scale constitutional change, as long as it happened. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hat taxes might be devolved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(for example, re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, Community Budgets, Government grant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s, formulas and taxes such as stamp duty)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All of the taxes mentioned above would be welcomed as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Even if the regulation of council tax was relaxed, instead of fully devolved, the impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on Wolverhampton </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would be positive. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Re-banding properties and the removal of the referendum threshold would give far greater freedom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and enable the local authority to respond to local needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The de-centralisation of stamp duty would enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to encourage regeneration in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> certain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, by reducing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or waiving stamp duty. The tax could also be used to discourage development in overcrowded areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The devolution of business rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has the potential to be beneficial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, if such devolution is comp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lemented by Single Pot funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It would enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to invest to save</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and enter into long term commitments with LEPs and other private sector partners, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a secure funding stream</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It would cut red tape, by enabling t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he local authority to give reductions when appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to encourage economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, rather than businesses having to negotiate a complex system of applying for a discount. Business owners would be able to scrutinise more closely the setting of business ra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tes, as they would be established on a local basis. It would enable the authority to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">engage with business leaders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and react more quickly to changing economic circumstances across the city. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However such freedoms would only produce economic growth if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they were supplemented by LEP Growth Deal funding to help tackle the barriers to growth in the Black Country. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These include contaminated land and a lack of infrastructure. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Flexibility regarding council tax and business rates would be welcomed in the short term before full devolution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occurs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What changes should be made to ‘devolved’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> authorities' borrowing powers</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">removal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ap on Housing Revenue Account borrowing. This would enable increased housing construction and a future revenue stream </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of rents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> paid to the council. Some l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evel of monitoring could remain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sensible construction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If councils were given full control o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ver business rates and their revenue, then more borrowing would not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">necessarily be needed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, a secure revenue stream would give councils more confidence to borrow. There should also be a change in the dialogue surrounding borrowing - rather than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> being seen as bad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">debt it should be encouraged, if carried out prudently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and sensibly, to stimulate growth. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Support from central government and Europe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for land remediation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would be necessary in order to make such projects financially viable for private investors. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he scope for areas to introduce new taxes and funding methods such as bonds and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rowd-sourcing, fees and charges</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The most appropriate scope would be to enable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authoritie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to raise funds by any means, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but not levy new taxes, unless they were accompanied with a very low administrative burden. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Revenue raising methods such as a local VAT would most likely result in excessive amounts of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bureaucracy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d tape.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Traded and non-statutory services should be allowed to make a profit, which would be re-invested back into the council. The local authority should have full discret</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion regarding fees and charges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including services such as licensing and planning. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, such discretionary charges could help discourage undesirable licenses being granted, or mitigate their effects, in a similar way to the night time levy (which should also be discretionary to adapt to local circumstance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he extent to which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> high-performing areas would be expected to redistribute their proc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">eeds of growth via the Treasury</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Redistribution of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proceeds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would need to be treated carefully. Some areas will still suffer from disproportionate stagnation and will need add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">itional funding, but local authorities should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be dis-incentivised to succeed. The level of revenue allowed before being re-distributed should be proportionate to the levels of deprivation within the area – the level of reward should match the effort in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vested. If some areas are very successful solely because of their location, their threshold should be lower. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The economic landscape of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is not a level playing field and such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">redistribution should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be used to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">address</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this inequity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton City Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> strongly emphasise the need for fairness in the redistribution of funds, and for the levels of deprivation within each devolved area to be taken into account when allocating funding. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>